ken/cost/latency envelope. default_variant high + variant_status accepted-unverified: GLM's native `reasoning_effort` has high/max, but whether opencode `--variant high/max` forwards to it is not confirmed — smoke-test, do not depend on it. Subscription billing: confirm dispatch cost via smoke test. GLM dispatch quirks (Z.AI docs): thinking on by default + preserved thinking on the Coding Plan endpoint; function-calling `tool_choice` only `auto`; streaming tool calls need `tool_stream=true`. Re-verify slug before dispatch (Z.AI ids drift).\"\n\n  Line 311:           \"benchmark\": \"008-glm-5.2-prompt-framework\",\n\n  Line 314:           \"sample\": \"5-framework bakeoff on invalid-dominant STRICT VALIDATORS (validate-ipv4 + validate-date + validate-semver), 3 samples/cell, real zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2 dispatches graded by the deterministic hidden-test oracle (grader noop, no LLM-judge bias). Run status SEPARABLE: per-framework correctness costar 1.0 = tidd-ec 1.0 = cidi 1.0 = race 1.0 (perfect tier) > rcaf 0.976 (the ONLY sub-perfect framework; also worst format adherence 0.889). Trust verdict TIE on correctness among the perfect tier (top-pair costar vs tidd-ec, margin 0, 90% CI [0,0]). costar is primary as best-of-tied: perfect correctness + tersest output (13 median words vs tidd-ec 38, cidi/race 94) + cross-model corroboration (also the empirical winner for kimi benchmark 007 and mimo benchmark 004). tidd-ec fallback (perfect, 2nd-tersest). rcaf avoided (only correctness misses + worst format). NOTE: CRAFT (the phase-1 doc-guided default) is NOT in the harness framework registry [rcaf,race,cidi,tidd-ec,costar] so it could not be benchmarked; the empirical winner among the 5 supported frameworks replaces it. 1/45 dispatches was a transient infra failure (exit -1, excluded from scoring).\",\n\n  Line 317:         \"profile_ref\": \"sk-prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md\",\n\n  Line 330:           \"quota_pool\": \"anthropic\",\n\n  Line 335:       \"primary_quota_pool\": \"anthropic\",\n\n  Line 336:       \"fallback_target\": null,\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt-models/SKILL.md:\n  Line 3: description: Per-model prompt-craft hub for small-model dispatch (DeepSeek-v4-pro + Kimi-k2.7-code + MiniMax-M3 + MiMo-V2.5-Pro + GLM-5.2 via cli-opencode). OWNS the per-model prompt-craft profiles in references/models/ (framework + scaffold + gotchas, mirroring model_profiles.json); executor MECHANICS (binary flags, invocation wrappers) stay in cli-opencode. Advisor co-surfaces it with that executor.\n\n  Line 8: <!-- Keywords: small-model, deepseek-v4-pro, kimi-k2.7-code, kimi-for-coding, minimax-m3, minimax-coding-plan, minimax-token-plan, minimax-api, glm-5.2, zai-coding-plan, z.ai-coding-plan, haiku, opencode-go, deepseek-api, context-budget, output-verification, model-profiles, structured-permissions, quota-fallback -->\n\n  Line 32: - Model names: `kimi-k2.7-code`, `deepseek-v4-pro`, `minimax-m3`, `mimo-v2.5-pro`, `glm-5.2`, `haiku`\n\n  Line 40: Before dispatching a small model, read `references/models/<id>.md` for that model's prompt framework (primary + fallback), pre-planning density, scaffold shape, and known gotchas. The profile mirrors `model_profiles.json` `recommended_frameworks` (DATA) and cites it; the WEIGHT of this skill lives in those on-demand profiles, not in this entry surface.\n\n  Line 69:     \"mimo\": \"mimo-v2.5-pro\", \"mimo-v2.5-pro\": \"mimo-v2.5-pro\", \"mimo pro\": \"mimo-v2.5-pro\",\n\n  Line 70:     \"glm\": \"glm-5.2\", \"glm-5.2\": \"glm-5.2\", \"glm5.2\": \"glm-5.2\", \"zai\": \"glm-5.2\", \"zai-coding-plan\": \"glm-5.2\",\n\n  Line 94:     model_profiles.json   # The registry DATA each profile mirrors\n\n  Line 198: 2. **Read the profile** — Open `references/models/<id>.md` for that model's prompt-craft: framework (primary + fallback), pre-planning density, scaffold shape, gotchas — mirrored from `model_profiles.json`.\n\n  Line 212: Canonical source: `sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json` (each entry's `executors` array enumerates the paths above).\n\n  Line 216: This skill OWNS per-model prompt-craft profiles (`references/models/<id>.md`) and the model registry DATA (`assets/model_profiles.json`); `cli-opencode` owns executor MECHANICS (flags, wrappers, budgets, permissions); `sk-prompt` owns generic framework definitions; `system-spec-kit` owns runtime helpers. See the Skill Boundary Map in §5.\n\n  Line 229: 2. **Mirror the DATA and cite it.** Each profile MUST reflect that model's `recommended_frameworks` (primary, fallback, avoid, pre-planning density, evidence) from `sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json` and cite it as the source of truth. When the registry changes, the profile follows.\n\n  Line 245: 3. A new small-model provider arrives that does not fit the existing quota-pool model. Update the registry schema in `sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json` first, then add the profile + index row.\n\n  Line 267: - [`sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json`](./assets/model_profiles.json) — Unified model registry; the DATA each profile mirrors (owned by this skill)\n\n  Line 279: sk-prompt-models (this skill)  ← OWNS per-model prompt-craft profiles + indexes + model registry (assets/model_profiles.json)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-sk-prompt-models-rename/006-regenerate-verify/spec.md:\n  Line 123: | REQ-004 | Routing + smoke | Advisor probe returns `sk-prompt-models`; a small-model dispatch resolves `model_profiles.json profile_ref → references/models/<id>.md` under the new path |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_templates.md:\n  Line 537: **When**: dispatching to MiMo-V2.5-Pro via the Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — primary slug `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` (provider `xiaomi-token-plan-ams`, quota pool `xiaomi-token-plan`) — or via the Xiaomi Direct API — slugs `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` and the low-latency `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` (provider `xiaomi`, pay-per-token; pick UltraSpeed for latency-sensitive checks/smokes — same COSTAR contract). The 126/004 benchmark (10/10 real `mimo-v2.5-pro` runs) found **COSTAR wins** (RACE is a statistical-tie fallback); use **lean-to-medium** pre-planning. MiMo is frontier-correct already, so frame for format + brevity, **not** guardrails — TIDD-EC/dense ranked LAST, and CIDI is unreliable (it intermittently writes to a file instead of returning inline code). **Always pass `--variant high`** — opencode maps low/medium/high to MiMo's reasoning effort (confirmed accepted on opencode 1.15.13); high is the standing default. **Omit `--agent`** (on opencode 1.15.13 `--agent general` warns and falls back to the default agent). Confirm live model ids with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Token Plan) or `opencode models xiaomi` (Direct API).\n\n  Line 543:   --model xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro \\\n\n  Line 551: **Invocation (Direct API — pay-per-token; swap in `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` for the low-latency tier)**:\n\n  Line 555:   --model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro \\\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt-models/README.md:\n  Line 40: `sk-prompt-models` is the per-model prompt-craft hub for small-model dispatch. It owns one prompt-craft profile per active model in `references/models/`, indexed by `references/models/_index.md`. Each profile records the model's primary and fallback framework, its pre-planning density, a tuned scaffold and a gotchas table. The profiles mirror `assets/model_profiles.json`, the registry that is the source of truth for context length, executors, quota pools and recommended frameworks.\n\n  Line 52: python3 .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py \"dispatch mimo-v2.5-pro through cli-opencode\" --threshold 0.8\n\n  Line 93: | mimo-v2.5-pro | COSTAR (fallback RACE, avoid TIDD-EC and CIDI) | lean | Empirical (benchmark 004) |\n\n  Line 99: `assets/model_profiles.json` is the source of truth. Each profile in `references/models/<id>.md` mirrors one row of that registry: the `recommended_frameworks` block (primary, fallback, avoid and density), the context length, the executors array and the quota pools. When the registry changes, the profile follows. When you need to know a model's dispatch paths or pool limits without reading the prose, open the registry.\n\n  Line 142: | Profile and registry disagree | The registry (`model_profiles.json`) was updated but the profile was not re-mirrored | Re-mirror the profile from its `model_profiles.json` row |\n\n  Line 145: | A model changed executors | The dispatch matrix row in `SKILL.md` §3 is out of date | Update the dispatch matrix row and the `executors` array in `model_profiles.json` |\n\n  Line 165: A: Follow the adoption checklist in `references/pattern_index.md` §4. The steps are: add a row to `assets/model_profiles.json`, add a row to `references/models/_index.md`, author the profile at `references/models/<id>.md`, add the dispatch matrix row in `SKILL.md` §3 and re-index the advisor. No code changes unless the model needs a new executor path in `cli-opencode`.\n\n  Line 181: | Profile mirror check | Diff each profile's framework block against its `model_profiles.json` row |\n\n  Line 182: | Benchmarks | Review the MiniMax benchmark 003, MiMo benchmark 004 and Kimi benchmark 007 evidence cited by `references/models/_index.md` and `assets/model_profiles.json` |\n\n  Line 194: | [`assets/model_profiles.json`](./assets/model_profiles.json) | The model registry data each profile mirrors |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:\n  Line 47: | MiMo V2.5 Pro (Token Plan) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n\n  Line 48: | MiMo V2.5 Pro (Direct API) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n\n  Line 49: | MiMo V2.5 Pro UltraSpeed (Direct API, low-latency) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n\n  Line 50: | GLM-5.2 (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan) | COSTAR + lean (empirical, benchmark 008) | [`glm-5.2.md`](../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md) |\n\n  Line 53: **Executor notes:** Omit `--agent` for all small-model dispatches listed above. OpenCode maps `--variant low/medium/high` to MiMo's reasoning effort; `high` is the standing default for MiMo. MiniMax Token Plan (`minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3`) and Direct API (`minimax/MiniMax-M3`) both serve M3. Xiaomi Token Plan (`xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro`) and Direct API (`xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro`) both serve MiMo-V2.5-Pro; the Direct API additionally serves `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, a low-latency tier with the same prompt contract. Ambiguous use-case (1 vs 2 vs 3) prevents the router from picking a path — resolve before dispatch. Always include a self-invocation guard signal when the dispatched session could loop back.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-sk-prompt-models-rename/spec.md:\n  Line 114: | 2 | 002-core-rename/ | `git mv` the folder; skill identity (`name:`, `skill_id`), internal back-links, `model_profiles.json` profile_refs | Complete |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt-models/references/quota_fallback.md:\n  Line 22: The fallback engine reads `sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json`.\n\n  Line 26: - `primary_quota_pool`\n\n  Line 27: - `executors[].quota_pool`\n\n  Line 28: - `fallback_target`\n\n  Line 34: Fallback is off today because every active model has `fallback_target: null`.\n\n  Line 76: | `xiaomi-token-plan` | `mimo-v2.5-pro` | none | Xiaomi Token Plan Europe. |\n\n  Line 92: - parsed registry from `sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json`\n\n  Line 104: 3. Read the failed model's `primary_quota_pool`.\n\n  Line 105: 4. Read the failed model's `fallback_target`.\n\n  Line 106: 5. If `fallback_target` is `null`, return `fail-fast`.\n\n  Line 109: 8. Compare `target.primary_quota_pool` with `failed.primary_quota_pool`.\n\n  Line 131: if (failed.fallback_target === null) {\n\n  Line 132:   return failFast(`${failed.primary_quota_pool} pool exhausted, no separate-pool fallback configured`);\n\n  Line 135: const target = registry.models.find((model) => model.id === failed.fallback_target);\n\n  Line 138: if (target.primary_quota_pool === failed.primary_quota_pool) {\n\n  Line 148: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/fallback-router.ts\n\n  Line 151: That helper consumes a normalized projection where `quota_pool` is derived from\n\n  Line 152: the registry's `primary_quota_pool`.\n\n  Line 165:   \"primary_quota_pool\": \"deepseek-api\",\n\n  Line 166:   \"fallback_target\": null\n\n  Line 188:   \"primary_quota_pool\": \"deepseek-api\",\n\n  Line 189:   \"fallback_target\": \"some-deepseek-api-model\"\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"fallback-router|createFallbackRouter|FallbackRouter|fallback_target|onFailureTarget|quota_pool|model_profiles|glm-5\\.2|mimo-v2\\.5-pro","time":{"start":1783486744757,"end":1783486744772}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_052acda78f57ba1d016a4dd9188cc08191b1da5b93a83e1e56"}},"id":"prt_f401808b1001P7rPu4Wrqq9zES","sessionID":"ses_0bfeb66ceffeH0lBIVcE9YycJ4","messageID":"msg_f4017d8f2001e8lzIoTRJJRaMt"}}
